Next week, the Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu will discuss the law on the provision of psychiatric care again.
Psychiatrists are the only specialists that require parental consent for a person under the age of eighteen to access their services.
Specialists involved in the work of the committee have repeatedly emphasized the need to change the law.
Ave Häkli investigated why the amendment has stalled in the Riigikogu.
A gap in the law does not allow young people under the age of eighteen to seek psychiatric help without parental permission.
Although the ruling elite has repeatedly affirmed the need to change the law, young people continue to be left without assistance every month.
Young people should have the opportunity to seek help for themselves at all times, regardless of what their family members think about it, meaning that the distrust of seeking help for mental health problems is not gone from all families.
The current law is largely based on the assumption that all children have supportive parents, a functioning family that can support their child and make decisions on their behalf.
Unfortunately, in my work and practice, I see that this situation is different, that not all parents know how or for some reason do not want to deal with their child's problem, if they may lack the necessary skills themselves, if they need help themselves, or even if they are the cause of their child's problems.
The Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu has discussed the issue six times.
Various aspects of the problem have been explained by specialists in the field.
Representatives of thirty-six organizations have also signed a joint appeal, which justifies the importance of amending the law.
A year and a half has passed since the Chancellor of Justice drew the country's attention to the fact that this small amendment would be fair and necessary for young people.
Today, we are in a situation where the Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu has been processing this issue for almost a year, including receiving support for this small amendment from the Ministry of Education, the Ministry of Justice, the Ministry of Social Affairs, very loudly, including the Prime Minister and the Minister of Social Affairs.
And still, we are processing it and it is not being processed.
What initially seemed like a small and simple amendment has grown into a fundamental opposition.
Urmas Espenberg, a member of the Social Affairs Committee and a member of EKRE, says that theoretically they agree that young people should be able to see a psychiatrist without parental consent in exceptional cases.
However, no agreement is reached in practice.
According to Espenberg, two exceptional cases where a young person could turn to a psychiatrist without a parent present are the absence of a guardian and domestic violence.
I definitely do not agree with the idea that everyone should start seeing psychiatrists on their own, so that any random child can go for counseling with a psychologist first, and then the psychologist will see what to do next.

What are the opponents of the law changes afraid of? Is it that they don't trust young people or they don't trust the professionals in the field, namely psychiatrists?

Espenberg highlights the need to collaborate with families as one of the main reasons, as well as fears that strong medications will be prescribed to young people.

But there is also the fear that mental health issues will become a trend or that young people will sell the prescribed medications on the black market.

Young people are prone to trying all sorts of things, and when it becomes known that anyone can get them, then the talk about antidepressants becomes widespread.

Then maybe they will start selling them to each other.

The psychiatrist dismisses the fears of the opponents of the law changes.

It is the doctor's task and competence to assess the patient's condition and act accordingly.

It is always the doctor's wisdom to see through these situations, to see for what motives people actually come and how this use of medication is, that there are rules to follow, which, if followed, will prevent most of these problems.

Both specialists in the field and youth workers consider the problem serious and in need of action.

I approached thirteen youth workers from four different institutions dealing with young people, and a third of them have actually encountered situations where a child needs psychiatric help, but it has not been found due to parental opposition.

I also ask them for stories.

The stories are sometimes, to put it mildly, frightening.

Two of these stories have reached attempted suicide, fortunately unsuccessful attempts, one of them is an ongoing process where the child does not dare to contact their parents, as their parents are strongly convinced that mental health issues are something that only crazy or severely mentally ill people have.

Urmas Espenberg suggests a solution that some other adult who deals with young people could issue a referral or permission to a psychiatrist.
In practice, it looks like this: we have various networks, such as youth and child protection networks, then there is the same police, where certain cases are registered, they can make immediate referrals there, then there are school psychologists available, whom you can turn to.
There are many possibilities, there are many psychologists in Estonia and they are all relatively underutilized.
So, here we should think about how to solve these things and not blame each other.
However, each intermediate step increases bureaucracy and requires additional resources.
Currently, there is a problem of fulfilling existing requirements.
Only thirty-nine percent of Estonian schools have a psychologist working.
This means that over half of the schools have to manage without a psychologist.
Where they are, they are very capable, and where they are not, there is a great shortage of them.
What happens when a person cannot get help in time?
In the case of mental disorders, one of the most common being depression, there is a high risk that it becomes chronic.
But before it becomes chronic, it ruins your quality of life, meaning that a young person cannot learn, cannot communicate, cannot fulfill themselves in life.
And they deviate from everyday life, meaning they go home, sit in front of the computer at first, and soon not even there, they lie in bed, eat at best.
They are completely hopeless and only think that the only solution would be to die.
