According to Maarja Kadastik, the creator of the coronavirus models, such rapid growth in infections is expected because the reproduction number, which indicates how many people one infected person passes the virus to, has been between 1.2 and 1.4 in the past couple of weeks.
By Saturday, this number had risen to 1.5, which means that two infected individuals passed on the infection to three others.
Even if the reproduction number doesn't increase, it would still pose a serious threat to the Estonian healthcare system, as hospitals would be dealing with COVID patients by the end of the year.
Although there has been much talk about whether there are enough ventilators for COVID-19 patients, according to Kadastik, the real crisis would be for the entire healthcare system.
If we do reach capacity for COVID patients, we will have to take them from other places because we can't mix COVID patients with regular patients.
And if the system completely spirals out of control, as it has in some places around the world where hospitals are filled only with COVID patients, then we will actually have a problem where we can no longer treat other conditions that are very treatable.
COVID departments also require significantly more staff, and therefore it is not possible to endlessly create more bed spaces there.
According to Kadastik, it would be wise to make an effort to get the situation under control before the critical limit is reached.
Based on the current numbers, she believes it is more accurate to speak of the beginning phase of a major wave rather than the spread of the disease in waves.
