Ott Nool talks about the weather for the upcoming week.
Good evening.
Gradually, it will get cooler outside, as tomorrow a high-pressure system will dominate the Baltic Sea region, with its center located over Poland. Along the edge of the high-pressure system, colder air from the northwest will reach the Baltic States and Finland, causing temperatures to drop below freezing overnight and creating a risk of slippery roads.
During the day tomorrow, a weak low-pressure trough from Finland will take advantage of the movement along the edge of this high-pressure system, bringing light precipitation to Northern Estonia.
On Tuesday, the low-pressure trough will move away towards Russia, and the high-pressure system will cover the Baltic Sea region.
However, there will still be moisture in the area, and as is typical for autumn, a high-pressure system does not always mean sunny weather.
Cloudiness will vary overnight, and there will be occasional rain showers along the coast.
The wind will blow from the west-northwest at two to seven meters per second, with gusts up to eleven meters per second along the coast.
The air temperature will range from minus two to plus three degrees Celsius, with occasional five degrees along the coast.
The morning will be mostly cloudy, but clearer skies can be expected in Southeast Estonia.
Rain will mainly occur along the coast, and the southwest to west wind will blow at three to eight meters per second, with gusts up to twelve meters per second. Additionally, along the northern coast, there will be a northwest wind at seven to twelve meters per second, with gusts up to sixteen meters per second.
In some places, the temperature may drop below freezing in the morning, and temperatures of minus one to plus five degrees Celsius can be expected, up to eight degrees along the coast.
During the day, there will be occasional light rain, and the chance of precipitation will decrease in the afternoon.
The wind will blow from the southwest and west at five to eleven meters per second, with gusts up to fifteen meters per second.
Temperatures will range from five to ten degrees Celsius.
Tuesday promises to be clearer, but Wednesday will become slightly more rainy, similar to the rest of the week.
The air temperature is lower compared to the previous week and stays between zero and four degrees Celsius at night, with temperatures expected to reach five to seven degrees during the day.
The days are getting shorter and the coolness is slowly creeping in.
